
<p>The following is a translation from the June 1999 issue of <em>Newtype Magazine</em>. It has been slightly edited for clarity and readability. This interview is conducted by Rikao Yanagita, an author, science lecturer, and senior researcher at the Dream Science Laboratory.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large"><a href="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png"><img loading="lazy" width="348" height="509" data-attachment-id="10331" data-permalink="https://tsukinomayu.com/2023/09/02/newtype-magazine-06-1999-interview-with-syd-mead/image-9-2/" data-orig-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png" data-orig-size="348,509" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="image-9" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png?w=205" data-large-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png?w=348" src="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png?w=348" alt="" class="wp-image-10331" srcset="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png 348w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png?w=103 103w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/image-9.png?w=205 205w" sizes="(max-width: 348px) 100vw, 348px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><strong>Syd Mead</strong>. Born in the USA in 1933. After working at Ford Motor Company and other companies, he&#8217;s since worked as a &#8220;visual futurist&#8221; for movies such as <em>Blade Runner</em> and <em>Alien 2</em>, as well as designing theme parks in various locations.</figcaption></figure></div>


<span id="more-10192"></span>



<p class="has-vivid-red-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-3d3b235ea249524475adf5fa8ef70f15"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline"><em>The Message in the Details</em></span></strong></p>



<p><strong>Rikao Yanagita:</strong> What was the concept behind the design of the Turn A Gundam?</p>



<p><strong>Syd Mead:</strong> This is a business, and we are in the business of redesigning the Gundam. Just like the &#8220;movie business&#8221; of Hollywood, this is the &#8220;animation business&#8221;. <em>Gundam</em> is a combination of an object and a story. I was honored and lucky to be asked to redesign the Gundam, which has a 20-year tradition and a large fanbase in Japan. It is very important that the audience remembers it forever. If they don&#8217;t like the design, then it can&#8217;t be called a success. Because of this 20-year tradition, it wasn&#8217;t a job that could be done with a lot of freedom. We couldn&#8217;t create it completely freely, and in that sense, there were a lot of restrictions. It had to be in line with the director&#8217;s story. <em>Gundam</em> has lasted for 20 years so far, and from now on&#8230; whether it will last for another 20 or 30 years, I don&#8217;t know&#8230; but I designed a zero-base design for the beginning of a new tradition and history. I approached this work with a &#8220;problem-solving&#8221; approach. Firstly, the design had to be one that fans would remember, and yet still be instantly recognizable as a new Gundam. Secondly, the design had to be simple enough so that the animation company could draw 4,000 animation frames in a week. And lastly, it must be something that can sell as a toy.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large"><a href="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="768" data-attachment-id="10322" data-permalink="https://tsukinomayu.com/2023/09/02/newtype-magazine-06-1999-interview-with-syd-mead/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1-mkv_snapshot_01-06_2020-04-01_20-02-29/" data-orig-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg" data-orig-size="1440,1080" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=663" src="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-10322" srcset="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=1024 1024w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=150 150w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=300 300w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg?w=768 768w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_01.06_2020.04.01_20.02.29.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">From the <em>Turn A Gundam</em> opening. Until now, many Gundams have been drawn in this &#8220;looking up from the chest&#8221; composition. </figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> While examining all the details I was able to understand your design philosophy, but what impressed me most was the cylindrical waist. Humans cannot act without upper body twists and turns. However, most conventional robots are a combination of square columns, which makes it impossible for the hips to twist.</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> Sunrise had two requests for the Gundam. One was to make it look glamorous, with a slender waist. The other was to move the position of the cockpit from the upper part of the body to the uterus position. </p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> I think the position of the uterus implies a &#8220;sense of mental stability&#8221;, but on the other hand it is the part of the robot&#8217;s body that has the least amount of movement.</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> Of course, since this is a robot it doesn&#8217;t have a gender, but at first I couldn&#8217;t understand why they had such an obsession with the word &#8220;uterus&#8221;*.<br>(*The request from Director Tomino was for a simple design and location of the cockpit. In <em>Brain Powerd</em>, the cockpit was positioned around the crotch area, which made the framing easier. The design request was based on these two basic premises.)</p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> The soles of the Gundam&#8217;s feet are high heels.</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> This is landing gear, which as a similar feeling to a ski boot. In reality, you have to cushion both the descent to the skies and the landing.</p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> What is with the &#8220;mustache&#8221;?</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> It is part of the helmet and cheek guard, although fans took it as a &#8220;mustache&#8221;. In short, it is an antenna, but when designing it I had to remember that it must be instantly recognizable as a Gundam. The antenna is necessary, but I didn&#8217;t want to put it in the same location as a conventional Gundam, so I chose this position instead. The one on the head is also an antenna. The mustache is in the image of a Japanese kabuto (headpiece), and the head is in the image of a topknot. In the West, it is the helmet of an ancient Roman warrior. The reason I put the mustache here is that, from a design strategy point of view, animation has movement, so it also works as a parallax*. <br>(*originally intended to measure the distance to a celestial body)</p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> Does that mean that perspective can be expressed by the direction of the mustache?</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> It is easy to put a perspective on the image from above or from the side.</p>


