<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large"><a href="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="768" data-attachment-id="10328" data-permalink="https://tsukinomayu.com/2023/09/02/newtype-magazine-06-1999-interview-with-syd-mead/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1-mkv_snapshot_00-54-770/" data-orig-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg" data-orig-size="1440,1080" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=663" src="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-10328" srcset="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=1024 1024w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=150 150w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=300 300w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg?w=768 768w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/08/egturn-a_gundam_bd_op11080p_10bit9bae0be1.mkv_snapshot_00.54.770.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">From the opening. The quickly moving Turn A gundam appears surprisingly compact. In that sense, it gives it an image closer to a human than a conventional Gundam.</figcaption></figure></div>


<p class="has-vivid-red-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-951dcdacf77bbace822325df64842cc8"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline"><em>Awkwardly designed human-based robots</em></span></strong></p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> What do you think of bipedal robots in Japanese anime?</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> For this project, I was asked to design a 20-meter tall robot with two hands and two feet and used a human as a reference. It may sound strange, but that&#8217;s the story. The Gundam is a heroic robot that is like a human being and has a human spirit. In contrast, the enemy characters are monsters, but in my mind they are physically twisted and not in the standard human form. Machines can have one leg or three. It would be nice if the director would write a story in which a one-legged robot appears. But methodologically and stylistically, I think two legs is something that feels natural for humans. In fact, there are myths of giants in every country, so it is natural that robots too have two legs. The dream of creating an automaton, which humans have been pursuing for hundreds of years, is a very ambitious one.</p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> Is a bipedal robot an effective one when it comes to working or doing a job?</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> We have to solve the balance first. Nature created the human body over tens of thousands of years, and when you think about it, it is the ultimate design. In fact, monkeys&#8217; bodies are also very useful. They can grab things with their tails, and they have a body shape where everything is useful. But when it comes to mobility, I think two legs is the ultimate solution. They can also jump. I am 65 years old now, and after the age of 30 our body shape changes. The belly starts to protrude, and from the spine down we start to look unattractive. So, rather than thinking about robots, it might be better to think about why humans are designed in such an awkward way. At the age of 65, I really wonder why we are made so awkwardly. Given today&#8217;s biotechnology, we may be able to design a new human form within 20 years.</p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> So do you think when those things become a reality that new stories and new heroes will emerge?</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> Maybe then we&#8217;ll have a hero running around with six or so legs.</p>



<p><strong>Yanagita:</strong> When you said that there was a story first, and from there the &#8220;Gundam&#8221; was born, it was as if you were talking about the birth of the animated robots we have been watching since we were small children.</p>



<p><strong>Mead:</strong> First, there was a story and a dream, and the robot was born from that. Therefore, Gundam is ultimately a friend and admirer of mankind.</p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" />



<p class="has-vivid-red-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-375bd6a8ce410e0c089ca3fc7abad76a"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline">After Word by Rikao Yanagita</span></strong></p>



<p>Just before the interview, I looked through Mr. Syd Mead&#8217;s art book. Artificial objects were placed with a clear presence in a space that gave the impression of an absorbing expanse. One wonders what kind of words can be uttered from the mouth of the creator of such a world. I was already excited even before the interview began. A large body greeted me, smiling, and with open hands holding a bag of sweets. That was Mr. Mead. I asked him a short question, and the conversation took off from there. Perhaps, whenever there&#8217;s a chance, ideas and images start to flow out of him like a torrent. He wants as many people as possible to have happy dreams. The smallest details of the Gundam are filled with this desire.</p>


